node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on August 09, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Sure, you could make banana pudding with store-bought pudding mix. But making it from scratch—in this case with the help of tangy mascarpone and rich sweetened condensed milk—is going to deliver a whole lot more creaminess and complexity, and only takes about five minutes more. You can find the recipe from @jessiesheehanbakes for this classic dessert at the link in bio. 📷: @emmafishman, 🍴: @rice.isnice, 🥣: @aeswist

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on August 08, 2021. May be an image of cherries and indoor.

node.text: Cherries are HERE! This ephemeral fruit has a short and sweet season, so it’s all the more important to have all the information you need before you start buying in bulk. What should you look for? What’s the difference between the sweet and sour varieties? Fortunately, we’re here to help. Check out the full article at the link in our bio. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on August 07, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Grilled chicken breast sometimes feels like a punchline—a dry, stringy afterthought that’s never really all that good. But that doesn’t have to be the case! If you want grilled white meat that’s moist and delicious every time, it really comes down to three things: Buying the right cut, nailing the internal temperature, and resting the meat properly. Also: Sauce is your friend. Hop over to the link in our bio for more grilling tips. 📷 : @emmafishman,🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @tripleppp

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on August 05, 2021. May be an image of drink and food.

node.text: Growing up in Kolkata, India, Tania Banerjee’s (@azureskyfollows) mother’s homemade sweet lassis were her favorite way to beat the heat on a steamy summer night. A creamy concoction of yogurt whisked with sugar, chilled milk, ice, and often topped with nuts and dried fruits, they’re cool, refreshing, and couldn’t be easier to make at home. Read more at the link in our bio. 📷: :@isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 28, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: When Jarett Melendez (@jamarmel) was living in Mexico, he’d hit up the nearest roadside vendor selling pollo al carbon—juicy, spice-rubbed grilled chicken—whenever he didn’t feel like cooking. When he moved to the U.S., he missed it so much that he developed his own recipe so he could eat it anytime he wanted. “Al carbon” specifically refers to charcoal, but don’t sweat it—a gas grill will work too. Get the recipe at the link in our profile. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 27, 2021. May be an image of cherries and indoor.

node.text: We love a good bag of sweet cherries, the kind you take to the beach and eat out of hand, spitting out the pits into the sand. So what about these sour cherries that everyone seems to be talking about? What’s the difference? Is one better than the other? Read more about sweet and sour cherries—and when to use each in your summer desserts—at the link in our bio. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

Ananya Kumar-Banerjee (@anannavia) owes their love of coconut chutney to their chithi pati (maternal grandmother’s sister), who served it alongside fresh dosas when Kumar-Banerjee studied abroad in India. Now, they keep their freezer stocked with frozen coconut so they can whip up a batch of this refreshing condiment whenever the craving strikes. Dollop it on sourdough toast with fresh ricotta, use it as a dip for crackers or veggies—it’s tangy, herbaceous, and incredibly versatile. Read more at the link in our profile. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 20, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: The secret to adding richness, umami, and some fermented funk to your food? Crab paste. It brings intense, nuanced flavors to the table straight out of the container, which is why it’s such a winner for quick recipes like this summery grilled rib eye. Read more on how to use this Asian grocery store staple at the link in our profile. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: @susietheodorou 🥣: @elle_jaime

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 20, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Sushi rice gets cooked with corn (including its cob!) in this easy, delicately flavored Japanese-style dish, and it’s our new favorite way to showcase fresh sweet corn when it’s in season. Think of it as a springboard for all kinds of summer meals—pair it with a simple protein and you’ve got dinner on lock. Get @hanaasbrink’s recipe for Summer Corn Rice at the link in our profile. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 17, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Nothing makes Irina Groushevaia (@groushevaia) more nostalgic for their Russian childhood than kabachkovaya ikra, a.k.a. Russian squash caviar. It’s a silky, jammy, flavorful spread made from summer squash cooked down with tomatoes, carrots, and other veggies, and is the perfect way to use up that overly ambitious farmers market haul or backyard garden bumper crop. Even better: It’s dairy-free, gluten-free, and can be endlessly modified to your tastes. Get the recipe at the link in our profile. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Saucy pasta might not be the first dish that comes to mind when you’re packing for a day at the beach. But for Carlos Matias (@shawtylos), Dominican spaghetti—a hearty dish of pasta with peppers, olives, capers, and chunks of salami bound in a creamy tomato sauce—is a seaside meal swimming with tradition. Read more about this iconic dish at the link in our profile. 📷: @emmafishman 🍴: Rebecca Jurkevich

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Basically on July 15, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: It’s hard to think of fried shrimp without also picturing gloopy batter and bubbling, splattering oil, which is why Joy Cho (@joycho_pastry) had mentally filed crispy shrimp under “things I enjoy but definitely won’t be cooking at home.” That is until she developed a method that got a similar result—golden, crispy shrimp—without deep-frying, that only required one pantry ingredient. Read more at the link in our profile. 📷: @isa.zapata 🍴: @rice.isnice
